The following index definition indexes the
`page_updated_by.first_name` field in the [sample collection](custom-analyzers-eg-coll) collection using a custom analyzer named
`asciiConverter`. The custom analyzer specifies the following:* Apply the [standard](standard-tokenizer-ref) to
  create tokens based on word break rules.

* Apply the `asciiFolding` token filter to convert the field
  values to their ASCII (American Standard Code for
  Information Interchange) equivalent.**Atlas UI:**Atlas UI<Tab tabid="visual-editor">
  Visual Editor

  - In the Custom Analyzers section, click Add
    Custom Analyzer.

  - Select the Create Your Own radio button and click
    Next.

  - Type whitespace in the Analyzer Name field.

  - Expand Tokenizer if it's collapsed.

  - Select whitespace from the dropdown.

  - Expand Token Filters and click&#x20;
    Add token filter.

  - Select wordDelimiterGraph from the dropdown.

  - Click Add token filter to add the token filter to your
    custom analyzer.

  - Click Add to create the custom analyzer.

  - In the Field Mappings section, click Add
    Field Mapping to apply the custom analyzer on
    the message field.

  - Select message from the Field
    Name dropdown and dateFacet from the Data
    Type dropdown.

  - In the properties section for the data type, select whitespace
    from the Index Analyzer and Search Analyzer
    dropdowns.

  - Click Add, then Save Changes.
</Tab>JSON EditorReplace the default index definition with the following example:```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "dynamic": false,
    "fields": {
      "page_updated_by": {
        "type": "document",
        "dynamic": false,
        "fields": {
          "first_name": {
            "type": "string",
            "analyzer": "asciiConverter"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "asciiConverter",
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "standard"
      },
      "tokenFilters": [
        {
          "type": "asciiFolding"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```**Shell:**MongoDB Shell```javascript
db.minutes.createSearchIndex(
  "default",
  {
    "mappings": {
      "dynamic": false,
      "fields": {
        "page_updated_by": {
          "type": "document",
          "dynamic": false,
          "fields": {
            "first_name": {
              "type": "string",
              "analyzer": "asciiConverter"
            }
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "analyzers": [
      {
        "name": "asciiConverter",
        "tokenizer": {
          "type": "standard"
        },
        "tokenFilters": [
          {
            "type": "asciiFolding"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
)

```The following query searches the `first_name` field in the
[sample collection](custom-analyzers-eg-coll) collection for names
using their ASCII equivalent.**Atlas UI:**Atlas UI- Click the Query button for your index.

- Click Edit Query to edit the query.

- Click on the query bar and select the database and collection.

- Replace the default query with the following and click
  Search:**Input:**```json
{
  "$search": {
    "index": "default",
    "text": {
      "query": "Sian",
      "path": "page_updated_by.first_name"
    }
  }
}
```**Output:**```json
SCORE: 0.5472603440284729 _id:  "1"
  message: "try to siGn-In"
  page_updated_by: Object
    last_name: "AUERBACH"
    first_name: "Siân"
    email: "auerbach@example.com"
    phone: "(123)-456-7890"
  text: Object
    en_US: "<head> This page deals with department meetings.</head>"
    sv_FI: "Cette page traite des réunions de département"
```**Shell:**MongoDB Shell**Input:**```json
db.minutes.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "index": "default",
      "text": {
        "query": "Sian",
        "path": "page_updated_by.first_name"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "page_updated_by.last_name": 1,
      "page_updated_by.first_name": 1
    }
  }
])
```**Output:**```js
[
 {
    _id: 1,
    page_updated_by: { last_name: 'AUERBACH', first_name: 'Siân'}
 }
]
```MongoDB Search returns document with `_id: 1` in the results because MongoDB Search
created the following tokens (searchable terms) for the
`page_updated_by.first_name` field in the document, which it then
used to match to the query term `Sian`:| Field Name                    | Output Tokens |
| ----------------------------- | ------------- |
| page\_updated\_by.first\_name | Sian          |
